[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'How to create a mind. Researchers are making LLMs that are based on the logic of our own brains, which I\'m really excited about. Our brains are spiking neural networks. The logic of our own brains and bodies and actions relies on spiking patterns. How our neurons'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'communicate results in action. It just so happens that you can create an AI that operates the same way. So, they\'re creating spiking neural networks that have been combined with LLMs, which makes a lot of sense. It\'s recently been'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'found that large language models tend to produce structures very much like our own brains, and there are some very good questions about that. It may be that language produces the structures of brains or brains produce the structure'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of language. Really, it\'s kind of a chicken and an egg deal here. But, combining spiking patterns with language is very intuitive. And one of the questions you may ask is, why do this? Why would anyone want to do this? Well,'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'current LLMs as we have them uses enormous amounts of power and energy and water, too. Water is not as renewable a resource as you would like to think. But, our brains are very efficient. 20 watts of power, not even a particularly'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bright light bulb. And spiking neural networks are much more efficient. So, combining LLMs with spiking patterns that help drive salience patterns, that is, you know, what it has to focus on, that would result in a much more'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'efficient LLM and use far less power. I really don\'t think we ought to be changing the entire electrical infrastructure of the planet to support AI. Yes, it is useful, but there are some problems with it. Which leads me to'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'another question that I have. When I talk about medical advancements or things with brain organoids, the reason that they haven\'t moved to people yet is because there\'s a great deal to discover. We need to find the most efficient method before we start'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rearranging somebody\'s brain. But, apparently, human beings are perfectly happy to rearrange infrastructure before we find the most efficient method. But, let\'s talk about building a mind, because I am really excited for this.'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'One of the things that LLMs lack that would give them consciousness, at least as far as we know, is long horizons. Most AI and most agents do have short horizons. They have a task that they need to complete, they complete it, and'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then they forget about it. But if we want to create something that has more of a mind that looks like ours, we need to give them long-term memory. Salients is a great way to start because it gives them something to focus on. You clearly'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are not taking in everything all the time. You would go insane. You also don\'t have access to every memory all the time. Somebody needs to tell you to think about your seventh birthday party. AI can work much the same way. You need to give it a focus, something that is'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'important, so it can forget what\'s not important. There\'s also the issue of neural reservoirs. So, not all of the AI should be operating all the time. That is massive, that uses way too much energy. So, it can activate little'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subsets of itself when it needs to think about a certain task or a certain memory. With the convergence of neuromorphic systems and spiking neural networks with LLMs, there\'s also a lot of great opportunities to create'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something that is more complex. When we\'re talking about biological neural networks, which are near and dear to my heart, like brain organoids, yes, they\'re the brains that you can grow and have brain computation, we have found that them being more complex, having more kinds of subsections and types of'

[03:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'neurons, makes them work better. And for AI, it seems to be much the same, but we need to incorporate Locat. But we need to incorporate representative models of these systems. A neuron is not just a one-way street.'

[03:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you look at what a dendrite looks like up there, it\'s going to make multiple connections through multiple areas. It\'s also going to have to remember the power that flows through it. So, when you approach a memory, it needs to be reinforced, and you also'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'need to be able to make multiple connections. And this may be very necessary for critical thinking. It\'s likely very necessary for memory, and that is something we have to give AI, a way to change based on the experiences it has in a way that is more human. One'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the important things to remember about spiking neural networks is that their logic operates very similarly to the logic in our own brains. They fail at a lot of things. One of them is creating an image. So, you might be able to think of an image using your brain,'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but it\'s not going to be an exact replica. Yes, some people have eidetic memories and they get it very close, but for most people, it\'s very unlikely to be anywhere in the ballpark. So, asking an SNN to do many of the things an LLM'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can do for us pretty easily depending on the model and the task is going to be an order of magnitude harder for a spiking neural network. But, there are many things that they do much better, which'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is why I\'m so excited about the marriage of the two, like identifying images with limited information. They\'re much better at what we would consider to be symbolic thinking, if you were to call it thinking at all. I know this is a very'

